\begin_layout Standard
Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Isomorphisms"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 ended by showing that all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector spaces are isomorphic.
 That means, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{6}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{5}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{2\times3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, and the vector space generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{\sin t,\cos t,\sin2t,\cos2t,\sin3t,\cos3t\}$
\end_inset

 are all isomorphic.
 The essential ingredient of elements of each space is an ordered list of
 six real numbers.
 Elements of any of these vector spaces can be represented by such a list.
 Addition and scalar multiplication in one can be accomplished just as well
 in another.
 Representation, addition, and scalar multiplication are not enough to distingui
sh one from the other.
 Yet it might be nice to be able to draw distinctions between them.
 After all, they are different types of objects.
 Polynomials and elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are functions.
 A list of real numbers is just a list.
 A matrix is yet a different type of object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important feature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 not included in the definition of a vector space is the dot product.
 We have seen that the dot product allows us to define the magnitudes and
 orthogonality of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If we could extend the idea of the dot product to any vector space in such
 a way that it may not be preserved under one-to-one and onto maps, it might
 prove a useful distinguishing feature.
 To do that, though, we would need to write down the essential features
 of the dot product and hope that, as an abstract list of requirements,
 other vector spaces would admit similar operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Representing elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by column vectors, the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{T}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Matrix-Multiplication"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=u_{1},u_{2},\ldots,u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=v_{1},v_{2},\ldots,v_{n}$
\end_inset

, then the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which we will begin to denote  
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}=u_{1}v_{1}+u_{2}v_{2}+\cdots+u_{n}v_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u} & =u_{1}u_{1}+u_{2}u_{2}+\cdots+u_{n}u_{n}\\
 & =u_{1}^{2}+u_{2}^{2}+\cdots+u_{n}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is, conveniently, the square of the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative (the squares of real numbers are nonnegative and the sum
 of nonnegative numbers is nonnegative).
 This seems like an important property of the dot product since square roots
 of negative numbers are not magnitudes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Length-and-Orthogonality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 it was shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}\bcdot\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 implying that the dot product is commutative.
 Commutativity (or lack thereof) is a fundamental property of any operator.
 Since the dot product is commutative it seems that any abstraction of the
 dot product should be commutative too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both nonnegativity (of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

) and commutativity (of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

) follow directly from properties of the real numbers.
 Another such property is a sense of linearity.
 For the dot product of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{w})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w}\bcdot\mathbf{v}\\
 & \text{and}\\
(c\mathbf{u})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =c(\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Can you show these identities are true using properties of real numbers?
 Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:dot-product-identities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since this property follows as a natural consequence of considering real
 number scalars, it seems like it also ought to be a requirement of any
 abstraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One final point about the dot product that cannot be proven from these four
 but is nonetheless a direct consequence of properties of the real numbers
 is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u}=0\text{ if and only if }\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Though we did not discuss it before, this fact shows that the dot product
 can be used to determine when a vector is the zero vector.
 Can you argue using properties of real numbers that the equivalence is
 true? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:dot-product-zero"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

