\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
One reason for using the words norm and orthogonal instead of magnitude
 and perpendicular is because magnitude and perpendicular have ingrained
 geometric meaning in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 that does not readily transer to objects such as matrices and functions
 or even 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>3$
\end_inset

.
 What would it mean for two polynomials to be perpendicular, for example?
 Is there some geometric way to visualize this? What would the magnitude
 (or size) of a matrix mean? Is there some way to visualize this geometrically?
 Likely you are coming up short of answers.
 No matter.
 If we can come up with an inner product on the vector space of polynomials,
 then orthogonality of two vectors (polynomials) is 
\shape italic
defined by
\shape default
 the requirement that their inner product be zero.
 This is the power of mathematical abstraction.
 A notion such as perpendicularity, which we can clearly see and grasp in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, can be extended to other sets where no analogous picture can be drawn.
\end_layout

